But Kerensky was scared Kornilov would have him killed.
Yet as you point out, Lenin made the very same tactical move in Spring 1918, and it proved immensely popular.
It's true, though, that the army didn't want to stop fighting (at least in the spring).
Kornilov didn't become a factor until after the collapse of Kerensky's offensive in the summer. After this, probably too late.
He tried to arrest Lenin. He couldn't find him, because he went into hiding.
For that reason, they did not actually stage an offensive until after Kerensky launched his in July 1917.
After the February Revolution, Germans actually halted operations on Eastern Front in hopes Russia would make separate peace.
Obviously Provisional Government didn't, and wasn't willing to, for exactly the imperial designs you cite. But what if they had?
I'm not saying Russians give up imperial ambitions. But stage tactical retreat a year earlier (at less immediate cost).
I know, but in my scenario they would have been irrelevant.
11. So no Soviet Union in Russia and a German victory on the Western Front in 1917, just as the US joined the Allies. A lot to chew on.
10. Germany's 1918 offensive nearly shattered the Allies on the Western Front in any case. They might well have won in 1917.
9. In other words, Germany could have launched its final offensive in 1917, before US troops arrived in force and with French army in mutiny
8. But a separate peace in Spring 1917 would have also meant Germany shifting all its troops to Western Front one year earlier than it did.
7. A separate peace would have allowed Russian government to focus on restoring the economy, and delivered on promise of real change.
6. Without constant Bolshevik agitation, the Petrograd Soviet was eager to compromise and, despite "dual power", presented little threat.
5. That would have cut off Lenin's main appeal (peace now) and his covert sources of funding (from Germany).
4. They would have had to abandon Serbia, and disavow any annexations, but they probably could have gone back to status quo ante.
3. I think Russia probably could have struck a separate peace with Central Powers on pretty favorable terms in Spring 1917.
2. The problem was Russia really was too weary to carry on the war, and when it didn't end, many felt February Revolution had failed them.
1. I was thinking today about If Russia's Provisional Government could have done anything to stay in power and not be overthrown by Lenin.
